  "prompt": "How is Earth's axis tilt measured?",
  "response": "Earth's axial tilt, or obliquity, is measured as the angle between its rotational axis and a line perpendicular to its orbital plane around the Sun, known as the ecliptic plane. Specifically, the axial tilt is defined as the angle between the Earth's axis (which runs from the North Pole to the South Pole) and a vertical line drawn from the center of the Earth to the ecliptic plane.\n\nCurrently, Earth\u2019s axial tilt is approximately 23.5 degrees, but this value can vary slightly over long periods due to gravitational interactions with other celestial bodies, such as the Moon and other planets.\n\nTo measure this angle, scientists use various methods:\n\n1. **Astronomical observations**: By observing the positions of stars and other celestial objects over time, astronomers can track the changes in Earth's orientation in space.\n   \n2. **Satellite measurements**: Modern techniques involve using satellites equipped with precise instruments to measure Earth\u2019s rotation and orientation. These measurements can provide accurate data on the axial tilt.\n\n3. **Geodetic methods**: Techniques like Very Long Baseline Interferometry (VLBI) and Global Positioning System (GPS) can help determine the orientation of Earth's axis by measuring positions of points on the Earth's surface.\n\nThese methods allow scientists to monitor changes in the axial tilt over time, contributing to our understanding of long-term climate patterns and seasonal variations on Earth.",
